<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus muricata </i>is a moderate-sized, closed-cone conifer that attains a height of 25 m. Plants produce cones at 5-6 years of age; cones remain closed for several years and open after fire or on hot days (Cope 1993e). Botanists have treated <i>P. muricata </i>in several ways (Millar 1988): Chemical and morphological traits of trees of <i>P. muricata </i>change near Sea Ranch in Sonoma Co. (Millar 1983, Millar and Critchfield 1988, Millar et al. 1988). Trees to the north have leaves with a blue cast (blue race), and those to the south have greenish leaves (green race). This pattern, however, is not well represented in the confusing taxonomy of the species (var. <i>borealis, </i>var. <i>remorata, </i>and var. <i>stantonii; </i>Millar 1986), but it matches better with changes in landscape patterns. Trees of the green race often occur as groves surrounded by chaparral. Those of the blue race mix with regional conifers, forming local forest types. The degree of cone persistence also varies among stands (Millar 1986, Sawyer 2006). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Pinus muricata </i>grows on the mainland from Santa Barbara to Humboldt Cos., as well as on the Santa Cruz and Santa Rosa islands (Barbour 2007). It grows in areas with spring and summer fog, which is important to its survival (Cope 1993e). Chaparral surrounds stands in the La Purisima Hills that occur on diatomaceous mudstone (Cole 1980, Vogl et al. 1977), in the hills north of La Honda Canyon (Schmalzer et al. 1988) in Santa Barbara Co., and near Erendira in Baja California. Stands on the Channel Islands differ in species composition from one another and from those on the mainland (Philbrick and Haller 1977).  In Humboldt and Mendocino Cos., <i>P. muricata </i>commonly occurs on shallow, poorly drained soils and mixes with <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea, P. contorta, Pseudotsuga menziesii, </i>and <i>Sequoia sempervirens </i>(Westman and Whittaker 1975). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Pinus radiata </i>is a fast-growing conifer that attains a height of 15-35 m and an age of 80-100 years. Trees produce cones at 5-10 years of age. Cones are generally serotinous and open after a fire or on hot days. Trees have intermediate shade tolerance. The species grows on nutrient poor, acidic soils in maritime zones with summer fog. Mainland trees occur as three discrete populations in cental California (Santa Cruz/San Mateo, Monterey Peninsula, and San Luis Obispo Counties) where they grow on windy, foggy slopes and terraces in the coastal marine layer (McDonald and Laacke 1990). <i>Pinus radiata </i>is a rare CNPS list 1B.1 plant. <br/>
<br/>
Plantations of <i>Pinus radiata </i> exist in the state and worldwide, but natural stands exist in only three disjunct areas in mainland California: near Año Nuevo, on the Monterey Peninsula, and at Cambria. Additional populations occur on Cedros and Guadalupe islands off central Baja California. Variations in age structure and species composition are high among the three mainland populations (Barbour 2007, Jones and Stokes Associates 1994b, 1996, Rogers 2002, Stephens et al. 2004, White 1999). Cylinder (1995) describes links between marine terrace conditions and <i>P. radiata </i>success. His proposed types suggest that stands dominated by <i>P. radiata </i>have similar species composition but differ structurally on each terrace. <br/>
<br/>
Some native stands appear to be stable or increasing. For example, McDonald and Laacke (1990) estimated that the southern forests of the Año Nuevo population had increased by 95 ha in recent decades. It is difficult to differentiate between natural and planted tree regeneration in any of the stands. Nevertheless, the total area currently occupied by <i>P. radiata </i>is probably no more than 8000 ha (Rogers 2002). Because of this species’ economic status and rarity, we know much about the species genetically (Rogers 2002). <br/>
<br/>
The separate <i>Pinus muricata</i> and <i>Pinus radiata</i> alliances in the 2009 version of <i>The Manual of California Vegetation, second edition</i> have since been combined into this alliance because of similar life histories and associated species (Rodriguez et al. 2017), though associations with <i>P. radiata </i>are comparatively quite rare. We need to sample and study the vegetation associated with both <i>P. muricata </i>and <i>P. radiata </i>throughout their range. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
