<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text"><i>Pinus muricata </i>stands are typically even-aged, originating after the periodic crown fire that is critical in regenerating stands. The historic fire return interval in Point Reyes National Seashore is around 40 years (Sugnet 1985). Seeds from the large numbers of closed cones stored in the canopy are released following a fire to germinate on the newly cleared soil surface. A hot, early fall burn at Point Reyes in 1995 killed most trees as it swept through the canopy. However, the following year, many thousands of seedlings were establishing below the dead trees. A controlled burn on Santa Cruz Island in 1996 was successful in establishing many seedlings in a relatively senescent stand (Davis and Borchert 2006, Stuart and Stephens 2007).

Stands of the Monterey Peninsula population of <i>Pinus radiata </i>appear even aged, originating after fires; without it, <i>Quercus agrifolia </i>will become more important in tree canopies (White 1999). Mature trees have thick bark and often survive low- to moderate-severity surface fires, but crown fires usually kill trees (Cope 1993f, MacDonald and Laacke 1990). Fire effectively opens the trees’ serotinous cones and creates a favorable seedbed for released seeds. Reproduction rates are greatest after surface fire in which the parent trees survive (Vogl et al. 1977). However, an investigation of the fire history of the Año Nuevo population (Stephens et al. 2004) came to the conclusion that <i>Pinus radiata </i>does not need periodic fire to be maintained (Davis and Borchert 2006).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
