    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Af, Ah, Aj-k). Larger <i>Pinus radiata</i> stands surround <i>P. muricata</i> stands on the Monterey Peninsula. The Irish Hills stand of Bishop pine, between Los Osos and Avila Beach, is mature, with pine pitch canker and some pine recruitment. The Lompoc stand of <i>P. muricata</i> is dense with young trees (D. Chipping pers. comm. 2003). The Monterey Peninsula stands of <i>Pinus radiata</i> where Vogl et al. (1977) determined stand tree density and size distributions was re-sampled by White (1999). He found the stands maturing. While McBride and Stone (1976) denoted two successional types, Cylinder (1995) proposed several cover types for that population without supplying plot data. We list these cover types below; they are best thought of as proposed associations. Other stand locations are near Año Nuevo and at Cambria.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ae, Ag-l). Stands of <i>Pinus muricata</i> in Marin Co. on Inverness Ridge in Point Reyes National Seashore and at Tomales Bay include <i>A. menziesii</i> and <i>Q. agrifolia.</i> In Sonoma County, <i>P. muricata</i> stands are extensive on coastal terraces near Salt Point and Ft. Ross State Parks. They also occur on nutrient-poor sandstone uplands on Gualala Ridge, mixed with maritime chaparral and pygmy forests of <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea</i> (Klein et al. 2015). <i>P. muricata</i> codominates with <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea</i> and <i>P. contorta</i> ssp. <i>bolanderi</i> in what is now the <i>Hesperocyparis pigmaea</i> alliance in pygmy forests of marine terraces in Mendocino County from just north of Fort Bragg southward (VegCAMP 2019). The<i> Pinus muricata - Chrysolepis chrysophylla / Arctostaphylos nummularia</i> association is associated with the oligotrophic soils of these terraces. Stands in Mendocino Co. at MacKerricher State Park also contain <i>P. contorta</i> ssp. <i>contorta.</i> Stands in Humboldt Co. are mainly on industrial timberlands. Those at Luffenholdz Creek near Trinidad offer an early description (Metcalf 1921), where <i>P. muricata</i> mixes with <i>Abies grandis, Sequoia sempervirens,</i> and <i>Tsuga heterophylla.</i> The extensive Gray Creek stand, the northern extent of the alliance, was logged in the late 1990s (CNDDB). In Patrick’s Point State Park, individual trees mix with <i>Picea sitchensis</i> at the species’ northernmost location. Planted </i>Pinus radiata</i> stands occur in Sonoma Co. (Klein et al. 2015) and elsewhere, but they are not considered here as part of the range of the native alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba, Bc). Stands of <i>Pinus muricata</i> in the Purissima Hills and the west end of the Santa Ynez Mountains (Minnich and Everett 2001) largely burned in the mid-1990s and now contain dense young pine trees surrounded by chaparral. On Santa Rosa Island, <i>Pinus muricata</i> stands are known from the northwest-facing slopes of Black Mountain and young pines are replacing decadent ones (Rodriguez et al. 2017). Recent drought has severely impacted most stands on Santa Cruz Island (J. Knapp, pers. Comm. 2018). Three stands on Santa Cruz Island sampled prior to controlled burns in 1994 (CVIS 1995) had many dead trees and a scattering of non-fire regeneration. Although most stands on this island were degraded or extirpated by past livestock grazing and recent feral pig rooting (Minnich 1980a, Minnich and Everett 2001), post-burn stands generally contain dense regeneration (R. Klinger pers. comm. 2000). New stands following controlled burns are emerging from island chaparral due to new colonization from windblown seeds. Burned in-situ stands are regenerating amongst sprouting <i>Quercus tomentella</i> and sprouting <i>Comarostaphylis diversifolia</i> and other mesic shrubs (TNC 2007). A dozen small stands exist in the coastal foothills southwest of San Vicente in northern Baja California, some in association with <i>Hesperocyparis forbesii.</i></li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands of <i>Pinus muricata </i>occur disjunct and localized; however, they range more widely and cover a wider array of ecological settings than other species of coastal closed-cone pine alliances. Conservation requires examples throughout the full range of environmental settings, and periodic fire is an important factor in maintaining these stands. <i>Pinus radiata </i>is also adapted to periodic fires.

The susceptibly of <i>Pinus muricata </i>to needle blight caused by <i>Dothistroma septospora </i>varies geographically (Ades et al. 1992). Trees in the northern populations (Humboldt, Mendocino, and Sonoma Cos.) are moderately susceptible for the first 5 years of life. Those from Marin Co. south are increasingly susceptible. Trees on Santa Rosa Island are resistant. Ectomychorrhizal fungi are symbiotically associated with stands, and the fungi vary significantly in species composition when comparing colonizing and mature stands (Taylor and Bruns 1999). 

Pine pitch canker, <i>Fusarium circinatum </i>, is an issue in an increasing number of <i>P. muricata </i>stands.  Pine pitch canker (<i>Fusarium circinatum</i>) is also currently a serious threat to <i>P. radiata </i>(Rogers 2002), possibly because the advanced age of many stands makes them more susceptible to disease.  The movement of pitch canker in California is likely tied in part to the use of <i>P. radiata</i> in Christmas tree farms, and the ability of <i>Fusarium circinatum </i> to survive on pine seed (Gordon et al. 2001). Several species of pine native to California are susceptible to pitch canker and so the increasing prevalence of the disease in <i>Pinus muricata </i> and spread through the horticultural trade in to <i>P. radiata </i> represents a threat to forests more generally (Camilli et al. 2013).

Also problematic for <i>P. radiata</i> is genetic contamination from nursery stock from non-native sources (Smith and Ferlito 1997) and the presence of <i>Genista monspessulana </i>in many forest stands. Residential development, however, may be the highest threat to mainland stands (Davis and Borchert 2006). Goats are the main threat to stands on Cedros Island, while a changing fire regime may threaten stands on Guadalupe Island (Rogers et al. 2005). </div>
</div>

    

    

